76561197971951603,Recommended,271970,22696272,"Posted: 28 April, 2016",all,EPGAH,"It's very retro graphics, on par with say SNES, but the gameplay is exquisite.You cannot Level, but the girls you take with you can.You can still accrue EXP, though, and you can give it to your girls, or use it as currency elsewhere.You get beat down by a SLIME in the intro, and resurrected in a tavern by a man called the Haremancer, who summons two girls to help you.Each townsperson you talk to gives you ONE MAXHP bonus, permanent. Since you start with a MAXHP of only 100, that's quite a bit more generous than it sounds! (Hint: This is a game where at high Levels, you regularly give and take blows of OVER 9000!)Buying or selling in town gives the TOWN EXP!That's right, THE TOWN can Level, but not you! You can still gain stats, though, from various ""Stat Up"" hearts or veggies.Rare, and if you find a merchant who sells them, very expensive. It's all about grinding, but it's not tedious.Eat your veggies enough, and you can become King of Level 1! (As in, your Level 1 self can fight alongside your Level 250 girls, and actually make a difference, rather than have to be coddled and protected, as you'd expect.)You can capture SOME monsters (The ones that don't move, either to chase or avoid you), and use them to defend the Town, if the girls you left behind are too low-Level to do the job. The monsters movement gives an element of strategy, in that if you get behind them, you and your girls get first strike. If they get behind YOU, THEY get a free hit on YOU!There are also Bonus Bosses, who are WAY harder than any other monsters in a given dungeon--UNTIL you figure out their ""Gimmick"", at which point they become basically pushovers. In other words, Puzzle Bosses.(One of them, in an EXCEPTIONAL creative twist, asks you trivia questions about the game, and if you get it right, she damages herself to the tune of half her MAXHP!)However, even Puzzle Bosses can be ""solved"" by simply Leveling your girls up enough and then walking all over the enemy.If your whole party dies in normal play, you get teleported back to the Haremancer, to get back up and fight again.And there are Bonus Dungeons, from the Challenge Tower to the Other World.In the Challenge Tower, you get to see if you actually contribute to the group or not, because YOU can't join, only the girls can go into the Tower. Every 5 floors, either your main character gets a 5 point buff in each stat, OR the game shows you a cutscene. You cannot use Items in the Challenge Tower, only Skills and Spells.Cutscenes are hilarious, though still low-res.Think of Lufia II's ""Ancient Cave"", if you ever played that on the SNES.The Other World is where all the Bonus Bosses you've already killed go so you can beat them again and get ""Other World Points"", which can be traded for the best weapons in the game, and the all-important Stat Up Items. Be careful, though, in the Other World, DEATH IS PERMANENT!There's even a fortune-teller who allows you to make temporary changes to the NEXT DUNGEON RUN ONLY!· Fewer monsters· More monsters· Only Armor in chests· Only Weapons in chests· Only Items in chests (As in potions or Stat Up Items)· A specific seed value for the next dungeon (Useful if you are trying to capture a monster or find a particular Bonus Boss)You can order ONE change. It will take effect on your next dungeon run, then the dungeons return to ""normal"", whatever that might mean in the case of such a whimsical game.And the girls themselves not only Level, but have Affinity with you. You can gain Affinity just by fighting with them at your side, or if you have money to burn, you can buy baubles at the ring store (Or sometimes find/get them free from townsfolk) and give those to a girl to boost her Affinity. Boosted Affinity boosts stats, at least that's what it says. There's supposed to be an onsen cutscene when you get your Affinity high enough...And one of the girls IS your daughter. At first, I thought they had just mistranslated ""Musume"" from the game's original title, which can mean ""daughter"" or just ""girl"".﻿The girls are wonderfully varied and well-written, from the standard schoolgirl and healer type (The healer is depressed because she's ""average"" and there's even a running joke that if she's not in your party and you talk to her, her name shows up as ""Passer By"", until she corrects it!), to an assassin, a steroid freak, a ghost, a witch, a robot, a maid, a street-waif thief (Who is a LOT more damaging than you'd expect from that description)...and another overpowered character who is holding back because she WANTS to instead of FORCED to like your character!Plus the daughter of your own hero, who looks very much like your hero, and has junior versions of your Skills.You can talk to them and learn more about them as their Affinity rises.Each character has different Skills, some are specialized to heal, some do massive damage to one target, some damage a whole enemy party (And enemy ""parties"" can be up to 20 monsters, or at least that's the highest I've encountered so far), so you will need to customize your party to your NEEDS, as in whether you're grinding on normal monsters, or tryring to speedrun the Final Boss of a dungeon or maybe one of the Bonus Bosses.Arguably the most important loot you can find are Summon Stones. Bring them to the Haremancer, and he can summon you more girls, or if you have all the girls that are currently available to you, then you'll get ""Memories"" instead, which allow you to gain the girls' Skills on your own character!All-in-all, it's a wonderful game, if you don't mind SNES-Level graphics!﻿ Or perhaps if you PREFER retro graphics."
,Recommended,271970,22926095,"Posted: 12 May, 2016",all,Swordbane,"Don't be daunted by the negative reviews. From what I've gathered, most of them was a result of the game crashing, which to be perfectly honest does happen. But lo and behold! Open the discussion forum for this game and you'll find an easy fix to the issue. The developer pinned the discussion thread in the hopes that it could help us unfortunate souls from lost progression torment.For those who have difficulty locating said solution need look no further. Just follow these simple easy instructions.- Close game- Open ""Run""- Type ""regedit""- In the menu bar at the top, go to ""Edit"" and then ""Find""- Type ""Enterbrain"" and press OK- Wait for search result to populate- Right-click on ""Enterbrain"" folder and deleteNow for the actual review. I gotta say, I enjoyed this game more than I thought I would. I found some of the conversations to be witty and charming, with a dash of humour all-around. Thyere's not much that hasn't been already said by others but a feature I found interesting is that if you take the time to read some of the item names and descriptions, you'll find that the humour is present there as well.An example would be the weapon Cross Sword.It's description is a 5 letter word that starts with S, the answer is Sorry. It took me a couple of moments to recognize the joke, but when it did, I actually laughed out loud (lame I know). Cross Sword = Crossword.But I do wonder how in the world did I have 2 save files with leveled up characters in the first 2 save slots, before even playing the game. I've heard of others whose save files have been overwritten. My condolensces, my advice is to save on the lower save files, or even better, have multiple save files so that the probability of your save files (and progress) disappearing would be lower."
