,Recommended,271970,32890979,Posted: 27 June,all,Cerzel,"Many RPGMaker games are focused on the humour of poking fun at RPG tropes, but many of them don't do that well. Hero and Daughter is one that does, with consistently funny writing and entertaining plot developments that keep each chapter fresh. While primarily a grinding game, H&D actually has competent gameplay as a result of the large cast with their diverse skills, town building elements, dungeon events, and very fast battles. There's a surprising amount of content in the game, with things only really starting to slow down in the second to last chapter, and the final chapter naturally offers you the ultimate bosses that you'll need hours of grinding to beat. Might be a pain for those total completionists, but if you're willing to pass on the bonus bosses you'll get a pretty well-paced and fun experience out of it."
,Recommended,271970,28651002,"Posted: 25 December, 2016",all,True Axiom,"This is a perfect example of not judging a...well, a game by its cover.Hero and Daughter: not the best name. RPGMaker: a bad first impression. A bunch of pictures of...let's say fanservice-laden ladies as your cover picutres: not great.But don't write this off! Hero and Daughter is a roguelikelike JRPG. There's an almost limitless amount of content. You build a team of extradimensional summons--for instance, a cyclops, a high-school overachiever, and a wrestler--and go off into random dungeons, building them and your town up to dizzying heights.You don't level, but don't let that get you down. You eat a lot, and eventually grow into a functional level one here.I dunno. The systems click together well. If you enjoy building a team out of miscellaneous parts, and also somewhat strategic JRPG combat, this is possibly the game for you!"
