76561197995595724,Recommended,271970,21314236,"Posted: 19 February, 2016",all,raggedrobin,"Finally. A light-hearted RPG Maker game of some quality. The girls' character designs are all great, the dialogue is short and to the point, the story is goofy but not tedious. There are lots of unlockables and a constant flow of treasures and abilities to unlock from each of the girls who resemble a variety of typical classes like Fighter or Mage.It's the frivolous, high-paced Dragon Quest knockoff you've been waiting for. Recommended to fans of Half-Minute Hero or Azure Dreams.The only caveat: this game is anti-grind, like Half-Minute Hero. You do a lot of running at high speeds and slaughtering parties of enemies at high speeds. The game makes fairly thin pretense at gameplay. That's why the steady stream of party member discoveries and unlockables is good, for feeding the frenzy. You're basically bingeing on cute unlockables."
76561197998851748,Recommended,271970,21554865,"Posted: 29 February, 2016",all,"Agro, Died, Etc.","So a cram school student, a cyclops, a robot, and a reaper walk into a bar...I tend to turn my nose up to most RPGmaker games that ask for money to cross the toll into the title screen, unless I see some significant work put into the game's assets by the developer - if you can't be bothered to put some time doing your own thing to make it look like it's higher quality than some of the best of the free games done in the RPGmaker program out there, then it's not worth my money.At first glance Hero and Daughter+ doesn't seem to do much, using basic art and sound assets, the only new assets I've noticed being the party member portraits.  Instead of focusing on making new graphics or sound, the devs have done significant work on mechanics and gameplay systems.The game goes through a pleasurable feedback loop of handling preparation of dungeon romps in town with facilities that level up as you spend money on their wares, increasing their inventory or effects, and interacting and leveling up your team of summoned party members before heading out.Dungeons themselves run off of a mild RNG permutation system, where the dungeons have at least 10 possible builds for each to go through, but the treasures/amount of monsters is diffrent upon each entry, certain dungeon builds will also have certain special bosses to fight, and you can adjust some of the variables of a dungeon before entry via a facility in town.  Monsters appear on the field, where running into them initiates a fight, and you have multiple enemy group types you can tell via their sprite, such as normal groups, mini-bosses, and special metal/gold slimes.  Special NPCs will also populate dungeons that add some variety in the form of mini-games or random chance events that can gamble with your stats/money in exchange for rare items.  Anytime you leave a dungeon, either via beating the dungeon's boss or being wiped out, you get to keep your experience and any items you've found.  There is also a chance of a random event playing out between characters when coming back from a dungeon.The game is very freewheeling with how it doles out improvements to your group, while your main character cannot level up, he can still accumulate experience which can be used as a special currency for certain facilities or as bonus experience for party members, and your party members already can level up incredibly fast.But most of all, your party members are powerful.  Any given character will feel like they would be completely overpowered in any other game given their special abilities.  Especially early on, unlocking a character's abilities is a treat in opening up new ways of completely stomping the opposition, and several characters can easily keep single enemies - bosses included - on lockdown.Do you need your party to have every stat buffed immediately with the possibility to constantly stack buffs?  There's a character for thatDo you need to do armor piercing multi hit combos to an entire enemy group? There's a character for thatDo you need to charm a boss?  There's a character for thatDon't take this as an endorsement of the game being easy, party synergy is a big part of this, but later game situations will take into account that you can do all of this.Getting said overpowered miracles of destruction requires summon stones, which you can get in chests, from bosses, or special challenges.   Any time a summoning stone is spent it gives you a random girl from the playable roster, and they take up place in the town's pub, where you can talk with them, give them gifts, or pour EXP from your personal stash into them.  It's ok to be greedy with snatching girls from various places across the multiverse, as any you leave in town while dungeon romping will help level the town up.The writing for all the game's characters is light hearted and goes for a rather teenage sensibility, there's not much in the way of long winded rants or incredibly serious and dire emotional scenes, everything is in service to the comedy and doing mild exploration of character personalities and backstories.While the game's content might seem sparse at the first glance of what you are dealing with, you can be assured it will offer up plenty of new features and optional challenges to do as you advance forward.   And if you should ever feel you might be getting a bit too overpowered, there are features down the line that allow you to adjust character stats as you see fit.I whole heartedly recommend this, it reminds me of the simple joy older console RPGs use to go for in the 90's, and if you recall the ""Ancient Cave"" from the lufia/estapolis series, then you have a similar idea at play here."
